==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Unclear. One hypothesis derives {{och-l|冬|tr=*tˤuŋ}} from the antenna-like upper part of an oracle-bone graph formerly read as {{zh-l|鼉}} (“crocodilian”) (e.g. {{w|甲骨文合集|合集}} 6163反, 7405反), but reinterpreted as {{och-l|螽|tr=*tuŋ}} (“katydid; locust”).<ref>羅睿晣（2025）。釋甲骨文的「鼉」字－兼論「冬」字構形可能來源。中國文字，(總第十四)，187-211。https://www.airitilibrary.com/Article/Detail?DocID=P20241129001-N202603170001-00009
</ref>

The word may be related to {{och-l|統|tr=*tʰˤuŋh}}(“thread-end; leading strand of silk”) and {{och-l|終|tr=*tuŋ}}.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=昸,㫡,𠔙,𣆼,𠘀,𣅈,𠘗}}

Possibly related to {{och-l|終|to end}} ({{zh-ref|Wang, 1982}}, {{zh-ref|Sagart, 2023b}}). Sagart (ibid.) also proposes cognacy to {{cog|cdm|त्‍युङ्‌हसा|tr=tyuŋh||at end, be weak, exhausted}}, {{m|cdm|द्युमःसा|tr=dyumʔ||at ease after completing work}}, {{m|cdm|द्युम्‌सा|tr=dyum||terminate, reach end; to be at end}}, {{cog|kac|chatum||end, finish}}, {{cog|lif|tr=tum-ma|t=ripe, mature}}, Proto-{{cog|sit-aao}} {{m|und||*a-thəm|end, finish}}.

